{"timestamp": "2026-03-11T18:32:19.485530", "event_type": "command_executed", "source": "router_collect", "data": {"time": "2026-03-11 18:32:19", "input": "slsa-status", "response": "It looks like you're asking about **SLSA status**, but could you clarify what you mean?\n\nIf you're referring to **SLSA (Supply-chain Levels for Software Artifacts)**, it's a security framework from **Google/OpenSSF** to ensure software integrity. As of now:\n\n- **SLSA v1.0** is the latest stable version (released in 2023).\n- **SLSA is active** and gaining adoption in CI/CD pipelines.\n- **GitHub**, **Google Cloud**, and **Kubernetes** are among the early adopters.\n\nIf you meant something else (like a specific project's SLSA compliance or a typo), let me know!", "source": "brain"}, "correlation_id": "auto", "user_id": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-03-11T18:32:53.735848", "event_type": "command_executed", "source": "router_collect", "data": {"time": "2026-03-11 18:32:53", "input": "learn about autonomous learning systems", "response": "Autonomous learning systems (ALS) are machines\u2014software, robots, agents, or entire fleets\u2014that improve their own performance without waiting for a human to label data, set new objectives, or re-write code.  \nThey are \u201cautonomous\u201d in three simultaneous dimensions:\n\n1. Data autonomy \u2013 they decide what to sense, store, discard, or request.  \n2. Learning autonomy \u2013 they pick representations, algorithms, hyper-parameters, and when to switch them.  \n3. Goal autonomy \u2013 they can refine, re-prioritise, or even generate new objectives while staying aligned with hard constraints.\n\nBelow is a field-guide that practitioners actually use, not a textbook table of contents. Skim the bold lines if you only need the 30-second version.\n\n-------------------------------------------------\n1. Architecture patterns that keep showing up\n-------------------------------------------------\nA. Curiosity-driven loop  \n   Intrinsic reward = prediction-error or state-novelty.  \n   Used when external reward is sparse or missing (e.g., rovers on Mars, warehouse sweepers).  \n   Key failure mode: \u201ccouch-potato\u201d agent learns to hallucinate uncontrollable noise to maximise curiosity. Cure: random-network-distillation or controllability bonus.\n\nB. Self-supervised \u2192 Self-generated curriculum  \n   1. Mine pseudo-labels (rotation, jigsaw, contrastive).  \n   2. Train a teacher policy that proposes tasks of intermediate difficulty.  \n   3. Gate new tasks with regret: if current policy > 90 % success, make task harder; < 60 %, easier.  \n   AlphaZero, MuZero, and recent open-ended Minecraft agents all use variants of this loop.\n\nC. Meta-gradient outer loop  \n   Maintain two sets", "source": "brain"}, "correlation_id": "auto", "user_id": null}
